observations.recommendation:
a. We recommended that the Municipal Mayor should require the;
Municipal Treasurer to locate the supporting documents of these payables and submit to the Municipal Accountant for examination.

b. Municipal Accountant to:
 1. undertake a thorough review and analysis of the details of the payable accounts; 

2. recognize/ set-up a payable account only if there is a valid claim against the Municipality of Hindang duly supported with complete documents; and

3. effect the necessary adjustments to revert to the appropriate fund the balance of prior years’ Accounts Payable which are not supported with valid claims.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the SWM – Focal Person should:
prepare the necessary documents required for incorporations to the Municipality’s SWM Plan so as to obtain the NSWMC’s approval;

strictly enforce existing laws and ordinances on proper solid waste management;

incorporate in the SWM Plan the conduct of necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized;

provide complete personal protective equipment and paraphernalia to protect the garbage collectors and other SWM personnel from the hazards of handling solid wastes;

deploy additional number of personnel at the facility to utilize optimally the available equipment; and

cause the repair/ replacement of blunt blades of old shredder/ hammer mill, and ensure that these are properly maintained and in good operating condition.

We recommended that the SB Secretary secure SB resolutions authorizing the hiring of job order personnel and furnish the Office of the Auditor copies thereof;
We also recommended that the HRMO prepare policies and/or manual on hiring of job order and submit copy to the audit team; and
Henceforth, strictly observe the above-mentioned guidelines in hiring JO personnel.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all properties of the Municipality and submit the Report on Physical Count of PPE on or before September 30, 2022;

Appoint a General Services Officer (GSO) to prepare and maintain property records such as Property Cards and PAR for proper property management;

Initiate the disposal of unserviceable and damaged properties in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and COA Circular No. 89-296; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to derecognize in the books the properties which are in the possession of DepEd/barangay to put the accounts in order.

5.We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:

a.Municipal Health Officer to submit a written explanation to justify the noted overpayment of SRA and AHDP granted to Healthcare Workers of the Municipality of Hindang;

b.Municipal Accountant to ensure that (i) all necessary supporting documents are attached to the claims before approving all payments and (ii) correct computation based on the guidelines set by Administrative Orders and Circulars are effected in determining the amount due to each claimant to avoid disallowance in audit; 


c. Individual recipients, without prejudice to the joint and solidary liability of those who authorized and certified the legality and propriety of the payment, refund the overpayment SRA and/ or AHDP.

7. We recommended for the Local Chief Executive to:

a. Direct the MSWD Officer to submit to the Audit Team additional Distribution List if any, of beneficiaries with their signature signifying receipt of goods and materials;

b. Direct the Inspection Officer to submit a written explanation as to why the inspection and acceptance date differs from the date of delivery;

c. Direct the MHO to submit to the Audit Team a certified list of Quarantined Persons indicating therein the period of confinement and a photocopy of their identification card and Work Schedule and DTR of frontline workers on duty in the quarantine facility.

d. Direct the Municipal Accountant to compute and impose Liquidated Damages on delayed deliveries as discussed in paragraphs 7.13 and 7.14

e. Demand from the contractor the “as built plan” and warranty security for structural defects, as discussed in paragraphs 7.15 to 7.17.

8.1 We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

 require the BAC Secretariat and Municipal Engineer to submit to the Audit Team for review and evaluation all the lacking documents enumerated in paragraphs 8.10 to 8.21;

henceforth, require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that payments should be made based on properly documented obligations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:

require the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking supporting documents within 5 working days from receipt of this AOM.  Henceforth, ensure that all transactions are supported with complete valid and legal supporting documents before forwarding the disbursement vouchers to the LCE for approval;

require the BAC to submit written explanation as to why the procurement, as discussed in paragraph 2.3 was made through emergency procurement instead of competitive public bidding.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the Chairperson of the Bids and Awards Committee to submit explanation why the documents were not attached to the Contracts/disbursement vouchers;

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the Proof of posting of RFQ, BAC Resolution recommending award of contract and its corresponding approval, Proof of posting of Notice of Award, Supplier’s Mayor’s Permit and Omnibus Sworn statement, are properly attached on claims using small value procurement and shopping whenever applicable.

12. We recommended that for future similar transactions the Local Chief Executive:

a.  issue an Acknowledgment Receipt for In-Kind Donations for DRRM or his authorized representative for the receipt of in-kind donations.

b. designate the office to receive all in-kind donations who will:

1. establish an inventory management system on receipt, distribution and/ or utilization of in-kind donations, and  

2. prepare the Summary/ List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances every month or every quarter supported by Acknowledgment Receipts, Proof of Receipt by and Distribution to the Beneficiaries/ end-users, and Inventory of Remaining Balances, and 

c. submit the same to the NDRRMC through the OCD, copy furnish the Municipal Accountant and the Audit Team within ten (10) working days after the end of each month or quarter;

d. submit to the Property Officer copy of the Acknowledgment Receipt for donated equipment and other tangible items which costs P15,000 or less and has a life of more than a year

g.require the designated Property Custodian to:

o. Maintain Stock Cards/ Property Card for all donations in-kind received and update regularly;

Maintain Registry of Donated Relief Goods for each kind of inventory items; 

Prepare Property Acknowledgment Receipt (PAR) for issuance of donated PPEs and Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for the issuances of tangible items which costs P15,000.00 or less and have a life of more than a year and are not considered as PPE to establish accountability over them and furnish the Municipal Accountant with the PAR and ICS; and

require the departments responsible for the distribution of relief goods and other supplies (MDRRMO and DSWDO) to submit Proof of Receipt by and Distribution to the Beneficiaries/ end-users to the Office referred to in letter (b);

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant summarize the data from the documents obtained, compare records with Registry of Donated Relief Goods maintained by the Property Officer or by the designated MDRRMO for check and balance, and accordingly disclose all necessary information in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the SWM – Focal Person should:
prepare the necessary documents required for incorporations to the Municipality’s SWM Plan so as to obtain the NSWMC’s approval;
strictly enforce existing laws and ordinances on proper solid waste management;
incorporate in the SWM Plan the conduct of necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized;
provide complete personal protective equipment and paraphernalia to protect the garbage collectors and other SWM personnel from the hazards of handling solid wastes;
deploy additional number of personnel at the facility to utilize optimally the available equipment; and
cause the repair/ replacement of blunt blades of old shredder/ hammer mill, and ensure that these are properly maintained and in good operating condition.
10.22	The Municipal Mayor gave us the assurance that the SWM Personnel In-charge and the whole management of the Municipality of Hindang will give their best efforts to carry-out the recommendations provided by the Audit Team.

We recommended that the Municipal Engineer, from the recorded projects in the books of the Municipal Accountant, identify the road projects that should be turned-over to the barangays and the Municipal Treasurer, in the absence of a General Services Officer, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Record the cost of the road lots of the Municipality;

Transfer the cost of the Barangay road projects to the books of the Barangay concerned;




Reclassify the drainage canals from Flood Control to Road Network;


Maintain property ledger cards for each public infrastructure, and

Effect corrections on the lapsing schedule to compute depreciation of each infrastructure asset.

11. We recommend that the Local Chief Executive:

     1. Reduce the number of Job Order Workers to ensure that functions  of
        existing regular employees are not performed by JOs;


     2. Follow the mandated daily minimum  wage  rates  prescribed  by  the
        RTWPB for Region VIII;
